Punk is chiefly American with some British influence

Post-Punk describes a broad range of punk subgenres, many of which were American (No wave, Noise rock, Art punk/Avant punk, Punk blues, Paisley underground, Shoegaze, Gothic rock, Deathrock, Post-hardcore),,,,

Heavy metal arose from Acid rock (American) and was both American and British in genesis. However, Britain didn't play such a big role in the genre post the mid-80s, whereas the US continued to innovate and dominate Heavy metal up until the 2010s.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114375391
The idea behind perfect 4ths is this idea of musical consonants ie. notes that sound unoffensive when played together. A typical consonant or "perfect" triad is a 4th, 5th, and octave. This is considered a 5th dyad with a stacked root and, by nature of being a 5th dyad that lacks a 3rd interval (or "power chord") it has no chord character, it's neither major nor minor, it's just "regular". That's why it's all 4ths tuning. It was made that way so the open chord doesn't sound like anything. By making the interval between G and B a major third instead, you could allow the top string to be an octave above the lowest string. (bass E to treble e)

I would definitely get an amp and not solely rely on interface. Why? Because you. eed to learn to play with a light touch, and modulate your volume through your playing. There's a very good argument for simplicity

posts.com:
>>114375670
The primary difference in tone between P and J basses is in regards to the J bass neck pickup. The bridge pickup isn't great sounding on its own. With a J you often use the neck one or a combination of both, but not usually the bridge by itself. With a PJ you get the P bass pickup + option to pair it with the bridge, again not using the bridge by itself. Because of this a PJ isn't a best of both worlds thing at all.

>>114376975
Then you’ll wanna go into it with basic theory terminology in your head and figure out what it means by playing. So, like, understand the rudiments of functional harmony and understand intervals and how they’re named. I iii vi chords are stable, IV chords unstable, strongly want to move to stable chords, IV ii chords can move both ways. You don’t have to really grasp voice leading just know that it exists, its very helpful in understanding melodic ideas as you start to internalize the music. That’s the biggest thing really- all the theory in the world is fucking useless if you haven’t internalized the music and trained your ear. Sing along while you practice scales, sing arpeggios over chords you're practicing, even if its bad; you’re not trying to become a singer (unless you are, then free practice), just getting the music inside your head so you can intuitively apply theory to the things you’re hearing.
https://youtube.com/playlist?list=PLDezhk4lPPNlnZYAFr9hThavHDx43Sp4e this playlist is solid for getting your toes wet, just enough to understand that the ideas exist before you dive in so that you’re learning with purpose instead of just stringing chord shapes together in the dark.

posts.com:
>>114377129

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114377390
Besides the ones in the playlist? Not really
Just learn your cowboy chords, all the chords of the C major scale can be played on the first three frets, and the C major chord itself is easy to play in all three of its inversions so you can start getting a feel for different chord voicings and how they play into tension in a harmonic context
Learn all the positions of the G major pentatonic scale and then try to figure out how to play a full scale from each starting position by ear, but make sure you’re not just going down the neck playing G major, A major, C major etc (if you start doing that and get confused, briefly look into what modes are- 2nd position is dorian, 3rd is phrygian, all you need to know is theyre the G major scale notes in a funky order, but training yourself to find them by ear will make you a better musician)
from there, youve just gotta work out how to build chords with the note relationships youve discovered by exploring, and doing this well help you get an internal grasp of like, what a major third, minor third, etc sound like
if you get snagged up at some point just ask here again, people are helpful

>>114376349
People tried making melodies with AI, and while AIs can come up with solid melodies and even chord progressions, a song is way more then just melodies and chord progressions, you need instrumentation and, most importatly, context. Even the greatest AIs aren't capable of introspection and often falter when coming up with clever ways of tying their own melodies and chord pregressions together. I think AI generated music WILL be possible someday, just not quite yet.

Even if AI generated music was possible, I really don't think anyone would care to listen to it, we value context too much, wether we like to admit it or not. Play the same song for 2 audiences, tell audience A humans made the song, tell audience B an AI made it, and most likely what will happen is audience A will like the song way more than audience B did.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com: You need to know a lot of theory for that

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114376569
I assume you play an instrument? Most songs start on a variant of the I IV or V of the key they’re in, which narrows your tonic selection down to five notes; from there, just listen. If you play an instrument you should be able to broadly hear chord functions (I iii and vi are tonic/stable, V and vii° are dominant and want to resolve to the tonic chord, ii and IV are mediant and can move either way) and if you can’t, listen more critically while you play. Identifying the dominant is arguably the easiest way to find the tonic, since you should be able to hear the tension and subsequent resolution. The more you listen and play the more you’ll be able to suss out voicings and stuff like sus chords and extended chords and how they function in harmony; it helps to be familiar with the instrument you’re trying to figure out by ear, at least imo, maybe there’s some level of further enlightenment where you can figure out complex harmonies stripped of timbre in your head

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114376569
Given that you have the root notes (what chord is being played) try what quality the chord is (major or minor), find where it's being played (which octave) and quadrant from there, find the other notes being played, if it sounds jazzier or more complex look then for extensions on the higher register or just like triads then just look for repeated notes

>What chord it is, find the root note
>Quality, find the third on the octaves

And then the extensions and bass
If it's a more complex chord look for the extensions on the higher registers
AND then for the bass use the go Root for the lowest note, if it sounds right then go for the next and if it doesnt try third and extensions until you go to the very first root note

If it's a cluster chord or it has a lot of notes in between just keep with looking from down to top with the previous method of matching notes on the octaves
>What chord it is, find the root note
>Quality, find the third on the octaves

>Find the extensions on the higher octaves if they are
>Then for the bass, the Roots notes first, compare that it sounds right on the lowest not, and if not, then go for the thirds and then the other extensions

>for clusters, keep matching close notes by octaves, going roots, thirds and extensions, down to up


Basically, find the the root notes and then the thirds, if it it's a more complex chord fin the higher extensions on the higher registers (cause it's easier) AND then the bass, on roots, thirds extensions order, for cluster or close notes in the middle use the same method that you used for the bass, but keep in mind that it's gonna be harder to distinguish, that's why you needed to find all the notes on the higher registers first

>>114376537
Guitar controllers do exist but people don’t like them because they’re shitty. It’s harder to emulate strings without actually using strings than it is to emulate keys without actually using keys. Both texturally and sonically. There are ways to make some pretty realistic guitar sound banks (GarageBand can even trick you into thinking you’re listening to real guitars if you know how to arrange deceptively enough) but it’s really hard to convincingly pull off stuff like feedback, sliding (intentional or otherwise), vibrato/bending, chugging, etc in a way that sounds natural. That’s why most electronic guitar packs you hear in music are used to deliberately construct a sound that lives in the uncanny valley rather than to try and imitate the real thing (think Oneohtrix Point Never’s work in Garden of Delete. The acoustic sections in I Bite Through It specifically.)
The same thing applies to the feel of strings. Shits just hard to replicate without using actual strings.

In general, keyboards are just simpler than guitars. You press a key, you get a sound. This translates better to software. Guitars are more dynamic. Most people who want to incorporate the guitar interface into software just straight-up plug their actual guitars into an interface and translate the signal to MIDI instead of buying an entirely separate instrument that doesn’t work as well.

>>114376537
We do have digital guitars, they're just not very interesting or useful.

Digital pianos & drums are useful because they can efficiently replace the real instrument for people who can't afford them or don't have the space for it. Not to mention, drums and pianos are *loud*, so the digital versions have an instant market for everyone who wants to play those instruments in an appartment. Professional musicians use digital pianos as well because moving around a real piano and having to re-tune it every gig is a logistic nightmare and usually not worth it.

Digital guitars have no purpose as a replacement for real guitars, since real guitars for beginners can be found for very cheap, and they're not very loud unless you plug them into an amp. Moving a guitar and its amplification to a gig is trivially easy, and a digital instrument would save you no space nor time in this context, so pro musicians don't need them either.

They might have a purpose as their own "thing", for controling electronic effects and whatnot (just like how digital drums can be their own "thing" by controling samples instead of imitating real drums), but even in that aspect they'll usually be outperformed by digital keyboards, which will consistently offer a greater range of control over the notes. That or you can just take your regular guitar and use it to control MIDI effects with the right software.

Its a marketing scheme that was drummed up around the release of 8 mile.

Most (if not all) artists on major labels have at least one person (if not a whole department) whose job it is to manage fan narratives. Their job isnt conventional marketing but to ensure that beneficial narratives take hold about artists, to be spread organically by fans. In college we had a guest lecture from a person from the marketing department at Def Jam (coincidentally eminem's original manger Paul Rosenberg is now CEO) who told us about this. They don't need to be true they just have to be easily spreadable arguments for fans to push forward or convince people to idolise their artist. An obvious example of this was the lil wayne goat propaganda. Whether you agree or not that this was true, theres no denying birdman started that narrative.

In eminem's case (beginning in his career rebirth after the 2000s, major rebrand) these are:

>eminem is an expert level rapper
His rhyme schemes aren't particularly noteworthy or complex among his peers or predecessors. This was not something people said at all about eminem prior to his major career rebrand. Eminem also doesn't ever really say anything particularly thought provoking or memorable (even in a funny way) on his songs, like say Nas.

>no one wants to go toe to toe with eminem
a number of artists have, he just doesnt have any notable beefs with people his size. Why would they randomly diss him? Back in the day he confined his insults to the latest tabloid regulars of the day, and never went after anyone likely to respond. He was even unsuccessful at that, being dissed by mariah carey. The label wants you to think prior to his arrival that rap music was a cartoonish battle rap scene with random lyrical bouts happening at all times to prove your place. This has never been the case.

Unironically it had the same progression as something like jazz.

For jazz:
>started in the 20-30s as popular dance music
>in the 40s and 50s it became bebop which moved away from the dance element and became more like music in its own right
>in the 60s and 70s it moved towards free jazz, which was musicians music, i.e. music that only other musicians listen to and appreciate
>it also branched off into fusion, where it blended with other genres to survive

Same shit happened with metal
>in the 70s and 80s it was accessible, radio-playable music. Generally musically interesting but exciting enough that a fairly normie crowd could listen to it and enjoy it
>in the 90s it started to become less accessible, despite some normie hits like the Black Album. Death and Black metal took the popular appeal out of metal and were designed for specific subcultures of people who already liked metal. Nu-metal did this a bit but retained some popularity.
>In the 00s it became music for the metal fan subculture only. Metal grafted onto hardcore to become metalcore, which is extremely inaccessible for normies.
>same thing in the early '10s with blackgaze, where it blended with shoegaze to evolve
>since then it has started drifting towards becoming Musicians Music with the rise of technical genres (e.g. tech death, tech thrash), djent etc

tl;dr natural life progression for a style of music

>>114376467
One point to add here being that metal has a volume issue

One of the reasons bass guitars were invented was because rock and roll bands in the 50s had started using electric guitars. However, because the rhythm section still used double basses (which are acoustic), there was a limit on how loud the guitars could be before they drowned out the bass. Having an electric bass guitar removed this cap and allowed for things like metal to be created.

Strangely we now also have electric double basses (Les Claypool uses them onstage occasionally) but they never made their way back into rock, bass guitars just became the standard

There are a lot of instruments you could add but unfortunately to date a lot of them have only been used for gimmick shit like accordions for folk/viking metal or whatever

Again, I agree that 15 is probably too young, but I think in general that we underestimate the emotional and cognitive maturity of teenagers and to an extent it becomes a self-fulfilling prophecy. If you don't expect anything from someone, there's no opportunity for them to rise to the occasion.

I think people are blind to the fact that during puberty, we mature rapidly mentally as well as physically. People assume teenagers are clueless because they lack life experience, but to an extent maturation is an internal process that occurs independent of life experience. A 17 year old has more in common mentally with a 24 year old than a 14 year old, even though the 14 year old is closer in age and probably hasn't experienced much less in life than the 17 year old has.

To bring it back to relationships with age gaps, I think you're dramatically overstating your case in saying that a relationship with a modest age-gap will "break your mind." How? Why? Where is the evidence? Can you separate any negative effects from the social stigma that such relationships have? Such relationships are typical and uncontroversial in Europe.

a common rhythm, especially with hip-hop and modern drum patterns, is having your kick on the one and a snare, clap or other mid range perc on the 2 and 4. When i started to make music i was very young. I used some shitty music tool for the playstation one. I had no idea about mastering and did the mastering basiclley right in the creation process.
Later on when i learned about mastering i still had my workflow on doing it with each sample right in the creation. This gave me a lot of headroom later on when doing the final mastering nowadays, ending up always with a kick that has too much energy.

In my shitty opinion, mastering is very important and can bring forth the real structure of the idea of an creation but you have to be very carefull. A low frequency rumbling around can become very loude when you go to the final mastering.

I keep continuing to master my samples right in the mix, keeping in mind how it might end up in the final stage when doing the (somewhat second) mastering.

When i watch someone else lifestream i see them doing a lot of comprasion in the mastering, something i never really needed to do.

>I-IV-V
Technically the correct roman numerals, but they need to be lower case because this is in a minor key. That's something you'll want to know if you ever want to use chord symbols like that to communicate with other musicians. And it matters because many songs use borrowed chords. If you're in the key of C:
>I-IV-V
C - F - G
>i-iv-v
Cm - Fm - Gm
>I-iv-v-IV
C - Fm - Gm - F

>>114364524
long everything, long releases, long reverbs, effects that dont hurt to hear for a long time. it always sounds so stupid to say but you do sort of have to just feel out how to take something and evolve it in a way you want it to but i guess thats advice for all kinds of music isnt it. you can try automating bpm to make it have less of a direct effect on the speed of your track because itll be constantly changing.

note holders are also pretty cool, see if the plugins you like have those and if they dont you might be able to get one in ur daw. they let you take things really slow while keeping them evolved. if you have keyboard with dials you can assign them to various aspects of a synth patch like wavetable position or fm amount or anything and then adjust those slowly. i guess there isnt really one specific way to make any kind of music and be guaranteed that it'll turn out exactly how you wanted it.

buying tips:
test it out first. music stores have a PC so you can

white buttons should be bright white. if yellow a smoker owned it.

tap finger pads as light as you once you find the lightest touch to register go around all 4 edges of each pad noting any spots where a light touch wont register (pads light up when a hit registers)

knobs should be tight. some get used more than others. slightly looser than the rest is ok. watch for the software while turning a knob to see if it jumps or twitches or even moves when youre not touching it. air duster can usually fix this but better to avoid.
make sure audio in/out and mic work. should probably test midi.

if all youre interested in is having pads for drumming etc and dont care about the maschine software go with a presonus atom. much cheaper and good pads.

maschine studio is an option. doesnt have line/mic in though. $200-250. guitar center insurance will replace it with an mk3 should anything happen. 3 years coverage for one is about $65.

>Elvis Costello Live 1977 Chicago
>First generation pop-punk, British Power Pop
This has been released under the titles Armed and Dangerous, as well as Exit, but this is the actual soundboard recording used for the WXRT "Unconcert" broadcast in 1978. (Called Unconcert because it was sponsored by 7-Up, The "Un-Cola") Believe it or not, Tom Petty and The Heartbreakers were the opening act at this show. This was just before Elvis Costello and The Attractions made their debut on Saturday Night Live, subbing for The Sex Pistols who cancelled. (THANKS, MALCOLM!) My Aim is True had just been released, but This Year's Model was just a few months away. (Songs from TYM were played at this show)
When you listen to this concert, you'll understand immediately why Elvis Costello and The Attractions were considered a "Punk" band, and why the first generation of punk rockers adopted them as their own until 1980.

Again, no video. My apologies.

Saw a dude on /mu/ wanting to listen to the band Pizza, which had a weird interaction with Don Cab. The Plenty of Swords blog is where I originally got the Pizza albums from, but they're actually hosted on the graphic design website of one of the old members or something. The following is the Don Cab context:

This all went down on Don Cab's last tour in 2000 and happened at The Middle East in Cambridge, MA. One of the dudes from Don Caballero got a big head and decided his band wouldn't play with any local opening bands. Apparently the booking people didn't get the memo, and the band Pizza was slated to play and the members were already unloading when Don Cab shows up. Damon of Don Cab talks to management and gets Pizza to clear out. Apparently Pizza didn't make a stink about because they got free drinks for the night, but the fans of Pizza were pretty pissed, and were chanting "PIZZA" for all of Don Cab's set while sporadically spitting and launching actual slices at the guys.

Tour diary of a Don Cab member that documents it:
https://mycophobia.org/doncab.html
Interview with a member of Pizza about it:
http://plentyofswords.blogspot.com/2014/03/pizza-loves-don-cab-conversation-with.html

No one at the time was claimimg such, despite the quote. What was experimental was taking the musical practice and applying it in a pop music context. The means simply weren't available for that to easily come together before the 60s onwards.

Every software VA synthesiser I have come across has a static top end that fuzzes out your mix and doesn’t possess the attack and tone of a real analog synth. Every parameter and function of hardware synth blows the shit out of software. This whole industry is a farce that has bred over 500million amateur dumbstep remixes on soundcloud. After using a real moog Low pass filter going back to a software synth and playing with the cutoff of the filter is a joke. Even a nord will blow the shit out of software synths. Those things have dedicated DSP’s to make the sound with? Duh?
Software will get better and no doubt one day sound better than these clunky electrical circuits but for now its a no brainer. Software has it’s limitations, but so does hardware. Many talented musicians have composed using digital instruments. For you to sit here and bash everyone because they don’t run out an buy some dusty 60’s synth is ridiculous.

By the way, my studio used to have over 7 keyboards with several racks of gear. Today, my studio is neat and tidy thanks to softsynths. My workflow is faster and easier. Sure I’ll dial up some analog gear if the project needs it, but it’s not a necessity and it certainly doesn’t determine if someone is talented or not.

I wonder if you have the same hate towards LCD TVs, CD players, HD, The Internet.

Technology moves and we as musicians have to move with it. Even analog keyboards got some hate when they first came on the scene.
I have looked at software synths and the only company I believe at this stage that does a reasonable job is G Force, but with software synths you tend to loose the compression and thickness that hardware produces, maybe in the future it will catch up but right now and at this moment no software emulations ( expect maybe Masters oftware hits sound different to his circle of unsigned friends… rent a crowd etc. ) come close.

I mean I have listed the moog replications and comparing them to the Classis Mini Moog D is like comparing Korean pop music against Deep Purple!!!!

By the way I’m in my early 30’s but the classic sounds of the analog synths I hope one day will be reproduced, I mean Korg are looking at reproducing the oddesy which is fantastic and means we all don’t have to pay massive amounts of money for a used analog synth.

Any way lastly I would like to share with everybody here the best hardware analog emulations and cheap analog synths that I have personally found the best on the cheap. >>114375197
Good soft synths can sound fantastic and yes the modulation options are limitless and you can create sounds that would require massive rooms of hardware to reproduce, but you cant just add a bit of random "humanising" to get the warmth of real hardware, the DCO / DCF on reaktor comes close to the real thing to my ears, but most soft synths do sound reedy and thin, no matter how good a sound card you buy it wont change that, I'm yet to hear a VSTI that can sound better than my Prophet or Roland real analog, it's not nostalgia, even modern bands use real analog, that riff from Prodigy's firestarter a VSTI? No it's from their namesake a Moog Prodigy. You might be hearing music every day and thinking hasn't technology come a long way and yet you're listening to 30+ year old gear without realising it. I just use both digital software and analog hardware, they're equally good in their own ways, why choose, anyone serious about sound experimentation will want all options open to them, there's no argument, the experiment above is perfectly valid it's stripping the synthesizers to the bare minimum oscillator, filter and ADSR, any good digital analogue simulation should sound good with just ONE oscillator filtered and no tricks to beef it up.

Please make sure you listen to the Cinram versions of the 2 studio albums, Canada prepared their first CD releases in the early 80s several months earlier than Factory in the UK and had to create their own master, which is actually noticeably better than the UK master (less compression, slightly different soundstaging, bit more clarity on some instruments). The mix being slightly different might take some getting used to, but Steve Hoffman Forums thinks these are the best-sounding versions of the albums and I'm strongly inclined to agree. Future CD issues in Canada just used the same Factory master as everywhere else so that first run of 80s CDs is the only one to use the superior unique masters. I spent years searching for them & put them up on Soulseek in lossless - search my username on there, currently "Rrobynne Mk. II". Most of my shares on there are stuff that can't be found anywhere else. No hoarder bullshit. Enjoy!
